"Smith B.J., Collier K.J.","Tolerances to diurnally varying temperature for three species of adult aquatic insects from New Zealand",2005,"Environmental Entomology","34","4",,"748","754",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-23444431807&partnerID=40&md5=52798928aaa2c3594ce1e682736b3421","National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research, Ltd., Box 11-115, Hamilton, New Zealand; Environment Waikato, Box 4010, Hamilton, New Zealand","Smith, B.J., National Institute of Water and Atmospheric Research, Ltd., Box 11-115, Hamilton, New Zealand; Collier, K.J., Environment Waikato, Box 4010, Hamilton, New Zealand","Adult survival is thought to be an important factor regulating the size of aquatic insect populations, yet very little is known about the factors that cause mortality during the adult stage. Percentage mortalities over varying time intervals and 96-h lethal temperature values (96-hdmax LT 50) were calculated for the adults of the common New Zealand caddisfly Hydrobiosis parumbripennis McFarlane (Hydrobiosidae) and stonefly Zelandoperla decorata Tillyard (Gripopterygidae), and 48-hdmax LT50 values were calculated for the leptophlebiid mayfly Acanthophlebia cruentata (Hudson) using an amplitude of diurnally varying temperature regimens within and outside the insect's normal environmental range. Maxima ranged from 18 to 40°C and amplitude varied from 6 to 18°C. Mortality of adult mayflies and caddisflies were consistently higher than that of stoneflies for all comparable diurnal temperature trials. Daily temperature maxima were more important than the diurnal range in regulating mortality, with a rapidly increasing mortality as temperature maxima exceeded 24 (Acanthophlebia) or 30°C (H. parumbripennis and Z. decorata). Interpolated LT50 values for diurnally varying air temperature regimens were ∼31-33°C for adult H. parumbripennis and Z. decorata and ∼28-29°C for Acanthophlebia adults. The LT50 value for Z. decorata based on diurnally varying air temperature regimens was ≈10°C higher than that for constant temperature regimens. These findings have potential implications for managing riparian zones alongside streams and also for predicting the impacts of global warming on aquatic insect distributions. © 2005 Entomological Society of America.","Adult aquatic insects; Global warming; Lethal temperature; Riparian; Thermoperiod","aquatic organism; population size; riparian zone; survival; temperature; Australasia; Eastern Hemisphere; New Zealand; World; Ephemeroptera; Hexapoda; Hydrobiosis parumbripennis; Insecta; Leptophlebiidae; Plecoptera; Trichoptera; Zelandoperla",,,,,,"Anderson, T., Influence of temperature on the sex ratio of Trichoptera in light-trap catches in western Norway (1978) Nor. J. Entomol., 2, pp. 149-151; Brakefield, P.M., Kesbeke, F., Geneotype-environment interactions for insect growth in constant and fluctuating temperature regimes (1997) Proc. R. Soc. Lond., 26, pp. 717-723; Briers, R.A., Cariss, H.M., Gee, J.R.H., Dispersal of adult stoneflies (Plecoptera) from upland streams draining catchment with contrasting land-use (2002) Archiv. Fur. Hydrobiol., 155, pp. 627-644; Briers, R.A., Cariss, H.M., Gee, J.R.H., Flight activity of adult stoneflies in relation to weather (2003) Ecol. Entomol., 28, pp. 31-40; Brindle, A., The effect of temperature and humidity on the flight of Trichoptera (1957) Entomol. Monogr. Mag., 93, pp. 63-67; Brittain, J.E., Life history strategies in Ephemeroptera and Plecoptera (1990) Mayflies and Stoneflies. Life Histories and Biology, pp. 1-12. , I. C. Campbell (ed.), Kluwer, Boston, MA; Brosofske, K.D., Chen, J., Naiman, R.J., Franklin, J.F., Harvesting effects on microclimate gradients from small streams to uplands in western Washington (1997) Ecol. Appl., 7, pp. 1188-1200; Carey, J.R., Insect biodemography (2001) Annu. Rev. Entomol., 46, pp. 79-110; Carpenter, S.R., Fisher, S.G., Grimm, N.B., Kitchell, J.F., Global change and freshwater ecosystems (1992) Annu. Rev